{{more footnotes|date=May 2017}} {{Infobox language |name=Chamalal |nativename=чамалалдуб мичIчI (çamalaldub miçʿçʿ) |states=[[Russia]] |region=Southwestern [[Dagestan]]<ref name="Ethmap">[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_map.asp?name=RUE&seq=10 Ethnologue language map of European Russia, with Chamalal in the inset with reference number 10]</ref> |ethnicity=[[Chamalal people]] |speakers=500 |date=2010 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Caucasian |fam1=[[Northeast Caucasian languages|Northeast Caucasian]] |fam2=[[Avar–Andic languages|Avar–Andic]] |fam3=[[Andic languages|Andic]] |fam4=Akhvakh–Tindi |fam5=Karata–Tindi |fam6=Botlikh–Tindi |iso3=cji |glotto=cham1309 |glottorefname=Chamalal }}
'''Chamalal''' (also called Camalal or Chamalin) is an [[Andic languages|Andic language]] of the [[Northeast Caucasian languages|Northeast Caucasian language family]] spoken in southwestern [[Dagestan]], [[Russia]] by approximately 500 ethnic [[Chamalal people|Chamalals]]. It has three quite distinct dialects, [[Gadyri dialect|Gadyri]], [[Gakvari dialect|Gakvari]], and [[Gigatl dialect|Gigatl]].<ref name="e18" />
==History== Chamalal is spoken in southwestern [[Dagestan]], [[Russia]] by indigenous [[Chamalal people|Chamalals]] since the 8th or 9th century. The ethnic population is approximately 5,000, with around 500 speakers. The language has a 6b (threatened) status.
==Geographic distribution== The approximately 500 ethnic speakers live in eight villages in the [[Tsumadinsky District]] on the left bank of the Andi-Koisu river in the Dagestan Republic and in the Chechnya Republic. The speakers are mostly Muslim, primarily following [[Sunni Islam]] since the 8th or 9th century.
===Official status=== There are no countries with Chamalal as an official language.
===Dialects/Varieties=== Chamalal has there distinct dialects: [[Gadyri dialect|Gadyri]] (Gachitl-Kvankhi), [[Gakvari dialect|Gakvari]] (Agvali-Richaganik-Tsumada-Urukh), and [[Gigatl dialect|Gigatl]] (Hihatl). There are also two more dialects: Kwenkhi, Tsumada.
===Derived languages=== Gigatl (Hihatl) and Chamalal proper (with Gadyri, Gakvari, Tsumada and Kwenkhi dialects) are considered to be sublanguages.
== Writing System == Chamalal is an unwritten language. Avar and Russian are used in school, and Avar is also used for literary purposes.
