{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=June 2018}} {{Infobox writer | name = Harivallabh Bhayani | image = HarivallabhBhayaniPic.jpg | caption = | native_name = હરિવલ્લભ ચુનીલાલ ભાયાણી | native_name_lang = gu | birth_name = Harivallabh Chunilal Bhayani | birth_date = {{birth date|df=y|1917|5|26}} | birth_place = [[Mahuva, Bhavnagar]], [[Gujarat]] | death_date = {{death date|df=y|2000|11|11|1917|5|26}} | death_place = | occupation = Literary critic, Linguist, Translator | language = [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] | nationality = Indian | education = * Master of Arts * Ph.D | alma_mater = [[Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan Educational Trust|Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan]] | period = | genres = | subject = | movement = | notableworks = * ''Rachana Samrachana'' (1980) | spouse = Chandrakala (m. 1950) | children = [[Utpal Bhayani]] | relatives = | awards = {{plainlist| * [[Ranjitram Suvarna Chandrak]] (1963) * [[Sahitya Akademi Award]] (1981) * [[Narmad Suvarna Chandrak]] (1985) * [[Premanand Suvarna Chandrak]] (1987) * [[Sahitya Gaurav Puraskar]] (1989) }} | signature = Harivallabh Bhayani signature.jpg | years_active = | module ={{Infobox academic | doctoral_students = {{plainlist| * [[Jayant Gadit]] * [[Urmi Desai]]}} }} }}
'''Harivallabh Chunilal Bhayani''' (26 May 1917—11 November 2000) was a linguist, researcher, critic and translator from India.
==Life== [[File:School of Languages in Gujarat University Ahmedabad.jpg|thumb|The School of Languages where Bhayani served as professor]] Harivallabh was born on 26 May 1917 in [[Mahuva, Bhavnagar|Mahuva]] to Dasa [[Shrimali]] [[Jain]] [[Sthanakvasi]] family of Chunilal. His parents died when he was young and was raised by his grandmother. He passed his [[matriculation]] in 1934 from M. N. High School in Mahuva. He went to Samaldas College, [[Bhavnagar]] and completed B. A. in Sanskrit in 1939. He completed M. A. in Sanskrit and Ardhamagadhi from [[Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan]], [[Bombay]] in 1941.<ref name=hb>{{cite book|last=Jani|first=Balwant|title=Eng Hem Chandra Barua|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WOpfQmlmfiwC&pg=PA1|accessdate=26 March 2017|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-260-2024-9|pages=1–3}}</ref> He married Chandrakala in 1950.<ref name="ReadGujarati.com 2010">{{cite web | title=ગૂર્જર ગૌરવ – ટીના દોશી | website=ReadGujarati.com | date=4 June 2010 | url=http://archive.readgujarati.in/sahitya2/2010/06/04/gurjar-gaurav/ | language=gu | accessdate=16 October 2016}}</ref> He completed his thesis on ''Paumachariya'', an epic poetry in [[Apabhramsha]] by Swayambhudev, and received Ph.D. under guidance of [[Muni Jinvijay]] in 1951. He was also influenced by [[Ralph Lilley Turner]] during this period. He was a professor at Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan from 1945 to 1965. He returned to [[Ahmedabad]] and joined School of Languages, [[Gujarat University]]. He taught there from 1965 to 1975. He voluntarily retired in 1975. He served as an honorary professor at [[Lalbhai Dalpatbhai Institute of Indology]]. He also served at [[International School of Dravidian Linguistics]] in 1980. He received honorary fellowship of the [[School of Oriental and African Studies]] of the [[University of London]] in 1993.<ref name=hb/> In 1993, he co-founded ''Anusandhan'', a journal featuring Jain literary works.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jainpedia.org/themes/people/studying-jainism/contentpage/6/index.html|publisher=Institute of Jainology|title=Indian centres of Jain research|first=Nalini |last=Balbir|accessdate =25 September 2014}}</ref> He died on 11 November 2000.<ref name=AGSI>{{cite book|title=અર્વાચીન ગુજરાતી સાહિત્યનો ઈતિહાસ - આધુનિક અને અનુઆધુનિક યુગ (History of Modern Gujarati Literature – Modern and Postmodern Era)|first=Prasad|last=Brahmabhatt |publisher=Parshwa Publication|location=Ahmedabad|year=2010|pages=312-314|language=gu|isbn=978-93-5108-247-7}}</ref>
==Works== {{incomplete section|date=December 2016}} Bhayani was a scholar of [[Sanskrit]], [[Prakrit]], [[Apabhramsha]], [[Old Gujarati language|Old Gujarati]] and other medieval Indian languages.<ref name="Datta1988">{{cite book|author=Amaresh Datta|title=Encyclopaedia of Indian Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zB4n3MVozbUC&pg=PA1697|accessdate=27 September 2014|volume=2|year=1988|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|isbn=978-81-260-1194-0|page=1697}}</ref> He applied [[Neogrammarian]] in the study of the [[Gujarati language]].
His written works include: {{div col|colwidth=22em}} * ''Vyutpattivicāra'' (1975) * ''Śabdakathā'' (1963) * ''Apabhramśa language and literature'' (1989) * ''Indological studies'' (1993) * ''Kāvyanuṃ samvedana'' (1976) * ''Racanā ane samracanā'' (1980) * ''Gujarātī bhāshānā itihāsanī keṭalīka samasyāo'' (1976) * ''Setubandha'' (2002) * ''Prācīna-madhyakālīna Kr̥shṇa-kāvya ane Narasiṃha-svādhyāya'' (1986) * ''Videharāja ane camatkārī '' (1982) * ''Lokakathānāṃ mūla ane kula'' (1990) * ''Śabdaprayogonī pagadandi par'' (1995) * ''Gujarātī bhāshāno laghu vyutpattikośa'' (1994) * ''Śodha ane svādhyāya'' (1965) * ''Gujarātī bhāshānuṃ aitihāsika vyākarana, Ī. sa 1150thi 1550 sudhī '' (1988) * ''Śabda-parisīlana'' (1973) * ''Lokasāhitya, sampādana ane saṃśodhana'' (1991) * ''Bhāratīya sanskāraparamparā ane āpano vartamāna'' (1994) * ''[[Rāüla vela of Roḍa]]'' (1996) * ''Anuśīlano'' (1965) * ''Bhāvana, vibhāvana'' (1991) * ''Kāvyavyāpāra'' (1982) * ''Śodhakhoḷanī pagadandḍī para'' (1997) * ''Kāvyakautuka'' (1987) * ''Kāvyaprapañca'' (1989) * ''Studies in Hemacandra's Deśināmamālā'' (1966) * ''Studies in Deśya Prakrit'' (1988) * ''Kamalanā tantu'' (1994) * ''Some topics in the development of OIA, MIA, NIA'' (1997) * ''Thodoka vyākaraṇa vicāra'' (1969) * ''Anusandhāna'' (1972) * ''Śodha aura svādhyāya'' (1996) * ''Muktak-marmara'' (1998) * ''Te hi no divasāh'' (1998) (autobiography) {{col div end}}
==Awards== He received [[Ranjitram Suvarna Chandrak]] in 1963, [[Premanand Suvarna Chandrak]] in 1987, [[Sahitya Gaurav Puraskar]] in 1989. He was also awarded [[List of Sahitya Akademi Award winners for Gujarati|Sahitya Akademi Award for Gujarati writers]] in 1981 for his critical work ''Rachna Samrachna'' and [[Narmad Suvarna Chandrak]] in 1985 for his book ''Kavyaprakash''.<ref name=hb/>
