{{Infobox language |name=Luoji |altname=Qixingmin |states=[[China]] |ethnicity=[[Bai people|Bai]] |speakers= |date= |ref=<ref name="Hsiu2013">Hsiu, Andrew. 2013. ''[https://zenodo.org/record/1127796 New endangered Tibeto-Burman languages of southwestern China: Mondzish, Longjia, Pherbu, and others]''. Presented at ICSTLL 46, Dartmouth College. {{doi|10.5281/zenodo.1127796}}</ref> |familycolor=Sino-Tibetan |fam2=([[Tibeto-Burman languages|Tibeto-Burman]]) |fam3=[[Lolo–Burmese languages|Lolo–Burmese]] |fam4=[[Loloish languages|Loloish]] |fam5=[[Nisoish languages|Nisoish]] |fam6=[[Northern Loloish languages|Northern Loloish]] |fam7=[[Nasu language|Nasoid]] |iso3=none |glotto=none }}
'''Luoji''' ([[wikt:Autonym|autonym]]: ''luo˧˩dʑi˧''<ref name="Hsiu2013"/>) is a moribund [[Loloish languages|Loloish]] language of [[Weining County]], [[Guizhou]], China that is spoken by the [[Qixingmin people]]. There are a few semi-fluent elderly speakers in Shejie Village 蛇街村, Yangjie Town 羊街镇, Weining County, with no fluent speakers remaining.<ref name="Hsiu2013"/><ref name="msealangs">Hsiu, Andrew. [https://sites.google.com/site/msealangs/sino-tibetan/luoji Luoji].</ref><ref name="Hsiu2017">Hsiu, Andrew. 2017. [https://zenodo.org/record/1122543 Luoji audio word list]. Zenodo. {{doi|10.5281/zenodo.1122543}}</ref>
==Classification== The Qixingmin speak a language closely related to the local [[Nasu language|Yi language]], which is intermediate between the Western and Eastern Yi dialects of [[Weining County]] (Weining 1997:328).<ref name="Weining1997">威宁彜族回族苗族自治县民族事务委员会编. 1997. ''Weining County Ethnic Gazeteer'' [威宁彝族回族苗族自治县民族志]. Guiyang: Guizhou People's Press [贵州民族出版社].</ref> Some vocabulary items differ, such as the word for 'chili pepper' ({{zh|辣椒}}), which is "zi 自" in the Western Yi dialect, "shapo 傻迫" in the Eastern Yi dialect, and "boji 薄几" in Qixingmin.<ref name="Weining1997"/>
However, the Qixingmin claim that they are distinct from the [[Yi people|Yi]], and that their ancestors spoke a non-Yi language that had become extinct centuries ago.<ref name="Hsiu2013"/>
Qixingmin is geographically located between the Western Yi and Eastern Yi areas. These languages are spoken in:<ref name="Weining1997"/> *''Qixingmin'' ("Qixingmin Liangzi" 七姓民梁子): Xiangshui 响水, Jinhai 金海, Sandaohe 三道河, Shejie 蛇街, Yangjie 羊街, and Yanjia 严家 *''Western Yi'': Guanfenghai 观风海, Niupeng 牛棚, Dajie 大街, and Longjie 龙街 *''Eastern Yi'': Yancang 盐仓, Jinzhong 金钟, and Ertang 二塘
